                      [crw_ashoe_groupinlab.jpg]

                                                                     [ChrisGregBobKatyIcebar.jpg]

   The Aircraft Laser Infrared Absorption Spectrometer (ALIAS) instrument
   is a high resolution four-channel scanning tunable Quantum-Cascade (QC)
   laser spectrometer (3.4 to 8 µm) that makes direct, simultaneous
   measurements of (e.g. HCl, NO[2], CH[4], N[2]O, CO, water isotopes)
   (including vertical profiles of the tracers) in the stratosphere and
   troposphere at sub-parts-per-billion sensitivities. The instrument
   weighs 160 lbs.

   The measurement technique is based upon using QC lasers operating from
   3.4 to 8 µm scanning over absorption lines recorded using second
   harmonic absorption spectroscopy over an 80-m pathlength in a 1-m
   multipass optical cell of the Herriott design. ALIAS has flown over 280
   times in 6 major NASA missions: AASE-II, SPADE, STRAT, ASHOE/MAESA,
   POLARIS, and SOLVE.

   For NASA's July 2002 CRYSTAL-FACE Mission out of Florida, ALIAS will be
   configured with 3 QC lasers to make in situ measurements of CO, CH[4],
   H[2]O, HDO, H[2]^17O, H[2]^18O, and ^13CO[2]/CO[2] from the WB-57F
   aircraft.

